Whats available from info.geoconnex.us?

collection_url <- "https://info.geoconnex.us/collections"
collections <- jsonlite::fromJSON(collection_url)

knitr::kable(select(collections$collections, title, description))
title description

HU04 Four-digit Hydrologic Subregion

HU10 Ten-digit Watersheds

Public Water Systems U.S. Public Water Systems

Lets use Arizona as our area of interest.

az_url <- "https://info.geoconnex.us/collections/states/items?STUSPS=AZ"
az <- sf::read_sf(az_url)
mapview::mapview(list(Arizona = az))

The search above gave us one state that we can retrieve by its ID. Below, we grab its JSON-LD format. Below, we print two text of what can be interpreted

accept_jsonld <- httr::add_headers("Accept" = "application/ld+json")

az_ld <- rawToChar(httr::GET(az$id, config = accept_jsonld)$content)

az_ld
## [1] "{\"@context\": [{\"schema\": \"https://schema.org/\", \"geojson\": \"https://purl.org/geojson/vocab#\", \"Feature\": \"geojson:Feature\", \"FeatureCollection\": \"geojson:FeatureCollection\", \"Point\": \"geojson:Point\", \"bbox\": {\"@container\": \"@list\", \"@id\": \"geojson:bbox\"}, \"coordinates\": {\"@container\": \"@list\", \"@id\": \"geojson:coordinates\"}, \"features\": {\"@container\": \"@set\", \"@id\": \"geojson:features\"}, \"geometry\": \"geojson:geometry\", \"id\": \"@id\", \"properties\": \"geojson:properties\", \"type\": \"@type\"}, {\"NAME\": \"https://schema.org/name\"}, {\"census_profile\": \"https://schema.org/subjectOf\"}], \"type\": \"Feature\", \"properties\": {\"fid\": 40, \"STATEFP\": \"04\", \"STATENS\": \"01779777\", \"AFFGEOID\": \"0400000US04\", \"GEOID\": \"04\", \"STUSPS\": \"AZ\", \"NAME\": \"Arizona\", \"LSAD\": \"00\", \"uri\": \"https://geoconnex.us/ref/states/04\", \"census_profile\": \"https://data.census.gov/cedsci/profile?g=0400000US04\", \"id\": \"https://geoconnex.us/ref/states/04\"}, \"id\": \"https://geoconnex.us/ref/states/04\"}"
az_ld <- jsonld::jsonld_flatten(az_ld)

az_ld <- fromJSON(az_ld)

This gives us some basic information. The @id here is especially useful. Note that the @id (the subject of all the triples in the document) is the same as the id of the State GeoJSON we mapped above and used to retrieve this JSON-LD document.

Notice that we can get a name using a linked data property https://schema.org/name here. This is an example of structured data that would allow automated creation of information products that is an aim of geoconnex.us.

az_feature <- sf::read_sf(az_ld$`@id`)

az_feature_name <- az_ld$`https://schema.org/name`[[1]]$`@value`

# Could make html links clickable in mapview

az_map_layer <- setNames(list(az_feature), az_feature_name)

mapview::mapview(az_map_layer)

Now lets pivot to look at some data thats available for NM. For this example, lets first find all the HUC08s in NM. For this example, well use a spatial intersection, but as geoconnex grows, these kinds of queries will be possible directly in the linked data.

hu08_url <- paste0("https://info.geoconnex.us/collections/hu08/items?bbox=",
                   paste(sf::st_bbox(az_feature), collapse = ","))

hu08 <- sf::read_sf(hu08_url)

mapview::mapview(list("HUC8" = hu08))

Now lets zoom in and look at the Upper Salt HU08.

hu08 <- filter(hu08, grepl("Upper Salt", NAME))

mapview::mapview(setNames(list(hu08), hu08$NAME))
